        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Dec. 10<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear General Strachey</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am very much obliged to you for having taken the trouble to write to me. The case of the Bees interests me much. In all parts of the world, I do not doubt from the size of their jaws that humble bees will be found to be the biters, &amp; hive-bees to profit by their work.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I think I have somewhere heard of land-shells descending in the curious manner which you describe by a thread of stiff slime—<ref target="#foot.f3"/> My son George will be pleased to hear that you will probably be successful in getting the Geograph. Soc. to have one of the new globes made—<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p>
<p>With many thanks pray believe me | yours very faithfully | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">1.2 from … jaws 1.3] <hi rend="italic">interl in CD’s hand</hi> </note>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9176.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Richard Strachey, 9 December 1873</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD refers to bees’ cutting holes in flowers to get at the nectar (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9176.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Richard Strachey, 9 December 1873</ref> and n. 3).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9176.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Richard Strachey, 9 December 1873</ref> and n. 4.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1224.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">George Howard Darwin</ref> had designed a portable globe (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9176.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Richard Strachey, 9 December 1873</ref> and n. 5).</note>
